{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f3f54c90-af3e-4f00-af4d-a8e4ff9bcdae","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS (NativeAOT, no `createdump`)\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain stack traces, register state, and loaded images.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** — before reproducing:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   After the crash, look for `/tmp/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Use `bt`, `register read`, `image list` to inspect state.\n\n4. **If core dumps are still missing**, macOS may redirect them through `ReportCrash`. Check:\n   ```bash\n   sudo launchctl list | grep ReportCrash\n   ```\n   You can temporarily unload it to let cores land on disk instead.\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` (it's a CoreCLR tool), so Apple's built-in crash reporting and `ulimit -c` core dumps are your primary recovery paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"910edda9-e7ff-4dd3-9cf4-52db2fac17e5","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"6803:247AEF:2D01189:31C22A8:69FD4286"},"id":"65317a2c-38ca-4fe5-bc13-d78f210c4ee2","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:55:28.775Z","parentId":"3fb4a776-01a1-4580-91b5-84d253b5ac41"}
